The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Tata Motors net up 52%

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Mumbai, May 17: Tata Motors has posted a 52 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 1,236.95 crore in 2004-05 compared with Rs 810.34 crore in the previous financial year.

 Total income rose to Rs 17,585.22 crore from Rs 13,282.12 crore.

 Net profit for the quarter ended March 31, 2005 rose 33 per cent to Rs 388.17 crore from Rs 292.47 crore in the corresponding previous period.

 Total income jumped to Rs 5,368.47 crore from Rs 4,152.41 crore.

 Total sales of 1,20,410 vehicles reflected a growth of 24 per cent over the 97,358 units in 2003-04. 

 The board has recommended a dividend of Rs 12.50 per share (including Rs 2.50 as a special dividend) of Rs 10 each for 2004-05, Tata Motors informed the Bombay Stock Exchange today. The previous years dividend was Rs 8 per share.

 The company has posted a 51.35 per cent rise in consolidated net profit at Rs 1,385.34 crore for the year ended March 31, 2005 against Rs 915.29 crore in 2003-04.

 Total income rose to Rs 19,666.78 crore against Rs 13,980.92 crore in 2003-04.

 The company is readying a a Rs 1400-crore capacity expansion plan, which will include development of new products. Last year, the company had invested Rs 900 crore. 

 The first quarter of this year is under tremendous pressure. It may not be very good as supplier issues and regulatory matters could affect the business, Ravi Kant, executive director of the commercial vehicle unit, said.

 Cost pressures are increasing and it is going to impact our bottomline, so we are going for the most aggressive cost reduction efforts in our history, said Ravi Kant. 

 Operating margins witnessed significant pressure due to an unprecedented increase in material costs like steel, the company said.

 Revenue for the quarter rose 29 per cent to Rs 5,338.87 crore from Rs 4,143.45 crore in the corresponding quarter of the previous year. 




